        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2472368228?book_show_action=true">May 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Danny Tyran" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Danny Tyran" href="/user/show/12973215-danny-tyran">Danny Tyran</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12973215-danny-tyran?shelf=freebies">freebies</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12973215-danny-tyran?shelf=i-have-one">i-have-one</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12973215-danny-tyran?shelf=horror">horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12973215-danny-tyran?shelf=culte">culte</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2472368228" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8863411202709032846">At the beginning, I liked this novel. The author sets up well the horrific situation of her story. And she gives us just enough information to sustain the atmosphere of horror she created. <br/><br/>Then I realized that it was a cult story and that the grave sin of the people in the village was abortion. That&apos;s when I started to back off. <br/><br/>I am an atheist and all these stories of people obsessed with a religion, whatever it is, makes me uncomfortable. For me, religions are just a bunch of lies passed down </span>
  <span id="freeText8863411202709032846" style="display:none">At the beginning, I liked this novel. The author sets up well the horrific situation of her story. And she gives us just enough information to sustain the atmosphere of horror she created. <br /><br />Then I realized that it was a cult story and that the grave sin of the people in the village was abortion. That's when I started to back off. <br /><br />I am an atheist and all these stories of people obsessed with a religion, whatever it is, makes me uncomfortable. For me, religions are just a bunch of lies passed down from parents to children for centuries. And considering abortion as an unforgivable sin is what I find unforgivable. In any case, I wanted to give the author the benefit of the doubt and went on reading her novel.<br /><br />But the straw that broke the camel's back is that the end is not an end at all. It's a cliffhanger.<br /><br />At the very beginning, I’d have given four stars to this book (one star removed mostly because of many mistakes). Towards the middle, I was leaning towards three stars. But because of the cliffhanger, I removed another star. When I know that a novel ends with a cliffhanger, I don't read it; but I didn't know that this time. And I certainly wouldn't encourage an author who uses this kind of pathetic process to get readers to read the sequels. So I give two stars to this novel.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8863411202709032846" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


